Gd$_{2}$Mo$_{3}$O$_{12}$ takes on several different forms with changing temperature (Yuan, 2001): \begin{itemize} \item below 159$^\circ$C it is in the orthorhombic ground state \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B3C12_oP68_32_2c_3c_12c-001}{$\beta$'-Gd$_{2}$(MoO$_{4}$)$_{3}$} structure. \item In the range 159-850$^\circ$C it is in the monoclinic \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B3C12_mC68_15_f_ef_6f-001}{$\alpha$-Gd$_{2}$(MoO$_{4}$)$_{3}$} structure. (Shown here) \item Above 850$^\circ$C it is in the tetragonal \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B3C12_tP34_113_e_ae_2e2f-001}{$\beta$-Gd$_{2}$(MoO$_{4}$)$_{3}$} structure. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-0.25in} 
 (Morozov, 2014) took the data for this compound at 293K. 
 The ICSD lists Eu$_{2}$(WO$_{4}$)$_{3}$ as the prototype for this structure, but we prefer to use Eu$_{2}$(MoO$_{4}$)$_{3}$ to keep these related compounds together.
